# NestJS module structure

Each domain gets its own module under `backend/src/<domain>/`:
```
<domain>/
  <domain>.module.ts
  <domain>.controller.ts
  <domain>.service.ts
  dto/
    create-<domain>.dto.ts
    update-<domain>.dto.ts
  <domain>.service.spec.ts   # unit tests
```
Domains so far: `auth`, `users`, `workspaces`, `projects`, `tasks`,
`analytics`, `gateway` (WebSocket), `health`, `common` (shared guards,
decorators, pipes), `prisma` (PrismaService, injected everywhere via DI —
never instantiate PrismaClient directly outside this module).

# DTOs and validation

- Every controller input is a typed DTO class with `class-validator`
  decorators (`@IsString()`, `@IsEnum()`, `@IsUUID()`, etc.) — never accept a
  raw untyped body.
- Use `@ApiProperty()` from `@nestjs/swagger` on every DTO field so Swagger
  docs generate automatically — this is the contract-first habit from prior
  experience, applied here as codegen-from-code instead of spec-first YAML.
- Global `ValidationPipe` with `whitelist: true, forbidValidationErrors: true`
  is set once in `main.ts` — don't re-validate manually in services.

# Auth & guards

- `JwtAuthGuard` protects any endpoint requiring a logged-in user — applied
  via `@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard)`, or globally with `@Public()` decorator to
  opt out for routes like `/auth/login`.
- Role checks for workspace membership (`admin` vs `member`) go through a
  custom `WorkspaceRolesGuard` + `@Roles('admin')` decorator — never inline
  `if (user.role !== 'admin')` checks scattered in service methods. One guard,
  one place, testable in isolation.
- Access token: short-lived, returned in the response body only, never set as
  a cookie. Refresh token: httpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict cookie, longer
  lived, stored (hashed) in the DB so it can be revoked on logout.

# Prisma usage

- All DB access goes through injected `PrismaService`, called from services,
  never from controllers directly.
- Use Prisma's `select`/`include` explicitly — don't return full rows with
  sensitive fields (e.g. `passwordHash`) by default. Prefer a `select` that
  names exactly the fields needed.
- For anything beyond a simple query (aggregations, time-bucketed grouping),
  it is fine to drop to `prisma.$queryRaw` — but parameterize it properly,
  never string-concatenate user input into raw SQL.
- Every schema change goes through `prisma migrate dev --name <description>`,
  never hand-edited migration files.

# WebSocket gateway

- One `TaskGateway` in `backend/src/gateway/`, namespaced per workspace room
  (`socket.join('workspace:' + workspaceId)`) so events never leak across
  workspaces.
- Every emitted event has a typed payload interface shared conceptually with
  the frontend (mirror the shape in the frontend's socket types, even though
  there's no shared package — keep them in sync manually and note it in a
  comment).

# Testing

- Unit tests (`*.service.spec.ts`) for business logic — mock PrismaService.
- e2e tests (`test/*.e2e-spec.ts`) using `supertest` against a real test
  database for auth flow and at least the task reorder endpoint (this is
  where the race-condition fix needs a regression test — see PROJECT_PLAN.md
  Phase 3).
- Do not skip tests for endpoints called out in PROJECT_PLAN.md's "Hunt for"
  notes — those are exactly the spots that need a regression test once fixed,
  or the bug can silently come back.
